TY  - JOUR
T1  - Regionalism in a Multilateral World
AU  - Ethier, Wilfred J.
Y1  - 1998/12/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/250045
DO  - 10.1086/250045
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1214
EP  - 1245
VL  - 106
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Recent regional initiatives have been addressed from a Vinerian perspective of trade creation and trade diversion. This is true of both policy?oriented economists, who tend to be critical of the initiatives, and theorists, who have added dynamic and gametheoretic elements to the Vinerian structure. This paper describes the stylized facts of much recent regional integration and develops an alternative model. The analysis suggests that regional integration, far from threatening multilateral liberalism, may in fact be a direct consequence of the success of past multilateralism and an added guarantee for its survival.
AB  - Recent regional initiatives have been addressed from a Vinerian perspective of trade creation and trade diversion. This is true of both policy?oriented economists, who tend to be critical of the initiatives, and theorists, who have added dynamic and gametheoretic elements to the Vinerian structure. This paper describes the stylized facts of much recent regional integration and develops an alternative model. The analysis suggests that regional integration, far from threatening multilateral liberalism, may in fact be a direct consequence of the success of past multilateralism and an added guarantee for its survival.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/250045
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/250045
Y2  - 2024/03/23
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Marginal Cost of Raising Tax Revenue and Redistributing Income
AU  - Allgood, Sam
AU  - Snow, Arthur
Y1  - 1998/12/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/250046
DO  - 10.1086/250046
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1246
EP  - 1273
VL  - 106
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We present analytic formulas for calculating marginal welfare costs when taxes are levied against the wages of a heterogeneous population of households and marginal tax revenue finances either the supply of a public good or lump?sum transfers. The formulas are applied to explain the wide discrepancy between estimates of marginal welfare costs for redistribution previously obtained through computer simulation procedures. Our calculations reveal that these procedures introduced lump?sum transfers that were not specified as part of the reforms to be simulated, but explain most of the differences between their estimates. We also show that welfare cost estimates are quite sensitive to the elasticity of labor supply with respect to exhaustive public spending.
AB  - We present analytic formulas for calculating marginal welfare costs when taxes are levied against the wages of a heterogeneous population of households and marginal tax revenue finances either the supply of a public good or lump?sum transfers. The formulas are applied to explain the wide discrepancy between estimates of marginal welfare costs for redistribution previously obtained through computer simulation procedures. Our calculations reveal that these procedures introduced lump?sum transfers that were not specified as part of the reforms to be simulated, but explain most of the differences between their estimates. We also show that welfare cost estimates are quite sensitive to the elasticity of labor supply with respect to exhaustive public spending.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/250046
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/250046
Y2  - 2024/03/23
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Transaction Services, Inflation, and Welfare
AU  - Aiyagari, S. Rao
AU  - Braun, R. Anton
AU  - Eckstein, Zvi
Y1  - 1998/12/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/250047
DO  - 10.1086/250047
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1274
EP  - 1301
VL  - 106
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper is motivated by empirical observations on the comovements of currency velocity, inflation, and the relative size of the credit services sector. We document these comovements and incorporate into a monetary growth model a credit services sector that provides services that help people economize on money. Our model makes two new contributions. First, we show that direct evidence on the appropriately defined credit service sector for the United States is consistent with the welfare cost measured using an estimated money demand schedule. Second, we provide estimates of the welfare cost of inflation that have some new features.
AB  - This paper is motivated by empirical observations on the comovements of currency velocity, inflation, and the relative size of the credit services sector. We document these comovements and incorporate into a monetary growth model a credit services sector that provides services that help people economize on money. Our model makes two new contributions. First, we show that direct evidence on the appropriately defined credit service sector for the United States is consistent with the welfare cost measured using an estimated money demand schedule. Second, we provide estimates of the welfare cost of inflation that have some new features.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/250047
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/250047
Y2  - 2024/03/23
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Absentee Bidders and the Declining Price Anomaly in Wine Auctions
AU  - Ginsburgh, Victor
Y1  - 1998/12/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/250048
DO  - 10.1086/250048
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1302
EP  - 1319
VL  - 106
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The anomaly is concerned with the observation that in multiple item auctions of identical objects, prices tend to decline over time. I show that in the case of wine auctions, which have been analyzed frequently, the anomaly is likely to be caused by the fact that most bids are entered by absentees, who use nonoptimal bidding strategies. Therefore, wine auctions can hardly be used to illustrate the standard multiple?object auction model.
AB  - The anomaly is concerned with the observation that in multiple item auctions of identical objects, prices tend to decline over time. I show that in the case of wine auctions, which have been analyzed frequently, the anomaly is likely to be caused by the fact that most bids are entered by absentees, who use nonoptimal bidding strategies. Therefore, wine auctions can hardly be used to illustrate the standard multiple?object auction model.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/250048
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/250048
Y2  - 2024/03/23
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Minimum Wage and Individual Worker Productivity: Evidence from a Large US Retailer
AU  - Coviello, Decio
AU  - Deserranno, Erika
AU  - Persico, Nicola
Y1  - 2022/04/12
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/720397
DO  - 10.1086/720397
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2315
EP  - 2360
VL  - 130
IS  - 9
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We study workers who are employed by a large US retailer, work in many store locations, and are paid based on performance. By means of a border-discontinuity analysis, we document that workers become more productive and are terminated less often after a minimum wage increase. These effects are stronger among workers whose pay is more often supported by the minimum wage. However, when workers are monitored less intensely, the minimum wage depresses productivity. We interpret these findings through an efficiency wage model. After a minimum wage increase, profits decrease, and a calibration exercise suggests that worker welfare increases.
AB  - We study workers who are employed by a large US retailer, work in many store locations, and are paid based on performance. By means of a border-discontinuity analysis, we document that workers become more productive and are terminated less often after a minimum wage increase. These effects are stronger among workers whose pay is more often supported by the minimum wage. However, when workers are monitored less intensely, the minimum wage depresses productivity. We interpret these findings through an efficiency wage model. After a minimum wage increase, profits decrease, and a calibration exercise suggests that worker welfare increases.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/720397
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/720397
Y2  - 2024/03/23
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Effects of Fluoride in Drinking Water
AU  - Aggeborn, Linuz
AU  - Öhman, Mattias
Y1  - 2020/10/01
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2021/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/711915
DO  - 10.1086/711915
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 465
EP  - 491
VL  - 129
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Water fluoridation is a common but debated public policy. In this paper, we use Swedish registry data to study the causal effects of fluoride in drinking water. We exploit exogenous variation in natural fluoride stemming from variation in geological characteristics at water sources to identify its effects. First, we reconfirm the long-established positive effect of fluoride on dental health. Second, we estimate a zero effect on cognitive ability in contrast to several recent debated epidemiological studies. Third, fluoride is furthermore found to increase labor income. This effect is foremost driven by individuals from a lower socioeconomic background.
AB  - Water fluoridation is a common but debated public policy. In this paper, we use Swedish registry data to study the causal effects of fluoride in drinking water. We exploit exogenous variation in natural fluoride stemming from variation in geological characteristics at water sources to identify its effects. First, we reconfirm the long-established positive effect of fluoride on dental health. Second, we estimate a zero effect on cognitive ability in contrast to several recent debated epidemiological studies. Third, fluoride is furthermore found to increase labor income. This effect is foremost driven by individuals from a lower socioeconomic background.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/711915
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/711915
Y2  - 2024/03/23
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Neolithic Agricultural Revolution and the Origins of Private Property
AU  - Bowles, Samuel
AU  - Choi, Jung-Kyoo
Y1  - 2018/11/28
PY  - 2018
DA  - 2019/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/701789
DO  - 10.1086/701789
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2186
EP  - 2228
VL  - 127
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Familiar explanations of why hunter-gatherers first took up farming?superior labor productivity, population pressure, or adverse climate?receive little support from recent evidence. Farming would be an unlikely choice without possession-based private property, which appears to have existed among rare groups of sedentary hunter-gatherers who became the first farmers. Our model shows that among them, farming could have benefited first adopters because private possession was more readily established and defended for cultivated crops and domesticated animals than for the diffuse wild resources on which hunter-gatherers relied, thus explaining how farming could have been introduced even without a productivity advantage.
AB  - Familiar explanations of why hunter-gatherers first took up farming?superior labor productivity, population pressure, or adverse climate?receive little support from recent evidence. Farming would be an unlikely choice without possession-based private property, which appears to have existed among rare groups of sedentary hunter-gatherers who became the first farmers. Our model shows that among them, farming could have benefited first adopters because private possession was more readily established and defended for cultivated crops and domesticated animals than for the diffuse wild resources on which hunter-gatherers relied, thus explaining how farming could have been introduced even without a productivity advantage.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/701789
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/701789
Y2  - 2024/03/23
ER  - 

